---

## Pipeline Steps

The preview deployment pipeline executes the following steps sequentially. If any step fails, the pipeline must clean up resources allocated in earlier steps.

### Step 2a: Update Deployment Status to `building`

```typescript
await db.update(deployments)
  .set({ status: 'building', updatedAt: new Date() })
  .where(eq(deployments.id, this.options.deploymentId));
```

### Step 2b: Build Docker Image

Clone the repository at the PR head commit and build a Docker image. The build pipeline from Phase 4 handles:
1. Shallow clone: `git clone --depth 1 --branch {branch} {repo-url}`
2. Checkout specific commit: `git checkout {commitSha}`
3. Framework detection (Next.js, Dockerfile, static)
4. Dockerfile generation (if auto-detected framework)
5. Docker build with appropriate tags

**Image tag format:**
```
{projectSlug}:pr-{prNumber}-{sha7}
```

Example: `myapp:pr-42-a1b2c3d`

The 7-character short SHA ensures uniqueness within a PR while keeping tags readable. The PR number prefix distinguishes preview images from production images.

```typescript
const sha7 = this.options.commitSha.slice(0, 7);
const imageTag = `${this.options.projectSlug}:pr-${this.options.prNumber}-${sha7}`;

const buildStart = Date.now();

// Use the build pipeline from Phase 4
const buildResult = await buildImage({
  repoFullName: this.options.repoFullName,
  commitSha: this.options.commitSha,
  branch: this.options.branch,
  imageTag,
  installationId: this.options.installationId,
});

const buildDurationMs = Date.now() - buildStart;
```

If the build fails, update the deployment record to `status='failed'` with the error message and exit.

### Step 2c: Load Preview Environment Variables

Fetch environment variables scoped to `preview` for this project:

```typescript
const envRows = await db.select().from(envVars)
  .where(
    and(
      eq(envVars.projectId, this.options.projectId),
      eq(envVars.scope, 'preview'),
    )
  );

const envMap: Record<string, string> = {};
for (const row of envRows) {
  envMap[row.key] = row.isSecret ? decrypt(row.value) : row.value;
}
```

Secret values are decrypted at this point (AES-256, key from AWS Secrets Manager). The decrypted values are written to a temporary `.env` file that is passed to `docker run --env-file` and deleted after the container starts.

### Step 2d: Stop Previous Preview Container (if exists)

Before starting the new container, find and stop any existing preview container for the same PR:

```typescript
const previousPreview = await db.select().from(deployments)
  .where(
    and(
      eq(deployments.projectId, this.options.projectId),
      eq(deployments.type, 'preview'),
      eq(deployments.prNumber, this.options.prNumber),
      inArray(deployments.status, ['ready', 'deploying']),
      not(eq(deployments.id, this.options.deploymentId)), // Exclude current
    )
  )
  .orderBy(desc(deployments.createdAt))
  .limit(1);

if (previousPreview.length > 0) {
  const prev = previousPreview[0];
  logger.info(
    { prevDeploymentId: prev.id, prevContainerId: prev.containerId },
    "Stopping previous preview container",
  );

  if (prev.containerId) {
    await dockerStop(prev.containerId, { timeout: 30 });
  }
  if (prev.port) {
    await portAllocator.release(prev.port);
  }
  // Note: Caddy route will be overwritten with new port (same hostname)

  await db.update(deployments)
    .set({ status: 'archived', updatedAt: new Date() })
    .where(eq(deployments.id, prev.id));
}
```

### Step 2e: Update Deployment Status to `deploying`

```typescript
await db.update(deployments)
  .set({ status: 'deploying', updatedAt: new Date() })
  .where(eq(deployments.id, this.options.deploymentId));
```

### Step 2f: Allocate Preview Port

```typescript
const portAllocator = new PortAllocator(db);
const port = await portAllocator.allocate(this.options.deploymentId, 'preview');

logger.info({ port, deploymentId: this.options.deploymentId }, "Preview port allocated");
```

If port allocation fails (all 1000 ports in use), the deployment fails. This is unlikely for a single developer but should be handled gracefully.

### Step 2g: Start Container

```typescript
const containerName = `${this.options.projectSlug}-pr-${this.options.prNumber}`;

const containerId = await dockerRun({
  image: imageTag,
  name: containerName,
  port: { host: port, container: 3000 },  // Map host port to container's 3000
  envFile: tempEnvFilePath,
  network: 'gblockparty',
  labels: {
    'gblockparty.type': 'preview',
    'gblockparty.project': this.options.projectSlug,
    'gblockparty.pr': String(this.options.prNumber),
    'gblockparty.deployment': this.options.deploymentId,
  },
  restartPolicy: 'unless-stopped',
});

// Delete temporary env file immediately after container starts
await fs.unlink(tempEnvFilePath);
```

Container naming uses `{slug}-pr-{N}` (without SHA) so the same name is reused across commits. Docker will require the old container to be removed first (handled in Step 2d).

### Step 2h: Health Check

Wait for the container to become healthy before routing traffic:

```typescript
const healthCheckPath = this.options.healthCheckPath ?? HEALTH_CHECK.DEFAULT_PATH;

for (let attempt = 1; attempt <= HEALTH_CHECK.MAX_RETRIES; attempt++) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(`http://localhost:${port}${healthCheckPath}`);
    if (response.ok) {
      logger.info({ port, attempt }, "Preview container is healthy");
      break;
    }
  } catch {
    // Connection refused or timeout -- container not ready yet
  }

  if (attempt === HEALTH_CHECK.MAX_RETRIES) {
    throw new Error(`Health check failed after ${HEALTH_CHECK.MAX_RETRIES} attempts`);
  }

  await sleep(HEALTH_CHECK.RETRY_INTERVAL_MS);
}
```

If the health check fails after all retries, the deployment fails. The container must be stopped and the port released (handled in the error cleanup path).

### Step 2i: Configure Caddy Route

Add a reverse proxy route in Caddy for the preview hostname:

```typescript
const previewHostname = `pr-${this.options.prNumber}--${this.options.projectSlug}.${domain}`;

const caddy = new CaddyClient();
await caddy.addRoute(previewHostname, port);

logger.info({ previewHostname, port }, "Caddy preview route configured");
```

The `CaddyClient.addRoute()` posts to the Caddy admin API at `http://localhost:2019`. If a route for this hostname already exists (from a previous commit), it is overwritten.

### Step 2j: Update Deployment Record to `ready`

```typescript
const previewUrl = generatePreviewUrl(this.options.projectSlug, this.options.prNumber);

await db.update(deployments)
  .set({
    status: 'ready',
    dockerImageTag: imageTag,
    containerId,
    port,
    url: previewUrl,
    buildDurationMs,
    updatedAt: new Date(),
  })
  .where(eq(deployments.id, this.options.deploymentId));

return { containerId, port, url: previewUrl };
```

---

## Error Handling and Cleanup

If any step fails after resources have been allocated, those resources must be cleaned up:

```typescript
async deploy(): Promise<{ containerId: string; port: number; url: string }> {
  let allocatedPort: number | null = null;
  let startedContainerId: string | null = null;

  try {
    // ... Steps 2a through 2j ...
  } catch (error) {
    logger.error(
      { error, deploymentId: this.options.deploymentId },
      "Preview deployment failed",
    );

    // Clean up allocated resources
    if (startedContainerId) {
      try { await dockerStop(startedContainerId); } catch {}
      try { await dockerRemove(startedContainerId); } catch {}
    }
    if (allocatedPort) {
      try { await portAllocator.release(allocatedPort); } catch {}
    }

    // Update deployment record to failed
    await db.update(deployments)
      .set({
        status: 'failed',
        errorMessage: error instanceof Error ? error.message : String(error),
        buildDurationMs: buildDurationMs ?? null,
        updatedAt: new Date(),
      })
      .where(eq(deployments.id, this.options.deploymentId));

    throw error; // Re-throw for the caller to handle (commit status, PR comment)
  }
}
```

---

## Integration with Steps 3 and 4

After the pipeline completes (success or failure), the calling function (from Step 1's `startPreviewBuild`) should:

1. **On success**: Call `setCommitStatus('success', { targetUrl: previewUrl })` (Step 3) and `createOrUpdatePRComment()` (Step 4)
2. **On failure**: Call `setCommitStatus('failure', { description: error.message })` (Step 3) and `createOrUpdatePRComment()` with failure status (Step 4)

This orchestration lives in a wrapper function:

```typescript
async function startPreviewBuild(
  db: Database,
  project: Project,
  deployment: Deployment,
): Promise<void> {
  const octokit = await githubApp.getInstallationOctokit(project.githubInstallationId);
  const [owner, repo] = project.githubRepoFullName.split('/');

  // Set commit status to pending
  await setCommitStatus(octokit, owner, repo, deployment.commitSha, 'pending', {
    description: 'Preview deployment building...',
    context: 'gblockparty/preview',
  });

  try {
    const deployer = new PreviewDeployer({
      db,
      projectId: project.id,
      projectSlug: project.slug,
      deploymentId: deployment.id,
      prNumber: deployment.prNumber!,
      commitSha: deployment.commitSha!,
      branch: deployment.branch!,
      repoFullName: project.githubRepoFullName,
      installationId: project.githubInstallationId,
    });

    const result = await deployer.deploy();

    // Set commit status to success with preview URL
    await setCommitStatus(octokit, owner, repo, deployment.commitSha, 'success', {
      targetUrl: result.url,
      description: 'Preview deployment ready',
      context: 'gblockparty/preview',
    });

    // Post/update PR comment
    await createOrUpdatePRComment(
      octokit, owner, repo, deployment.prNumber!,
      formatDeploymentComment('ready', result.url, deployment.buildDurationMs),
    );
  } catch (error) {
    // Set commit status to failure
    try {
      await setCommitStatus(octokit, owner, repo, deployment.commitSha, 'failure', {
        description: `Preview deployment failed: ${error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Unknown error'}`,
        context: 'gblockparty/preview',
      });
    } catch {}

    // Update PR comment with failure
    try {
      await createOrUpdatePRComment(
        octokit, owner, repo, deployment.prNumber!,
        formatDeploymentComment('failed', null, null),
      );
    } catch {}
  }
}
```

---

## Docker Commands Reference

The pipeline uses the Docker Engine API (via `dockerode` or CLI wrapper). Key operations:

| Operation | Docker CLI Equivalent | Notes |
|-----------|----------------------|-------|
| Build image | `docker build -t {tag} .` | Via build pipeline from Phase 4 |
| Run container | `docker run -d --name {name} -p {hostPort}:3000 --env-file {file} --network gblockparty --restart unless-stopped {image}` | Returns container ID |
| Stop container | `docker stop --time 30 {containerId}` | 30s graceful timeout |
| Remove container | `docker rm {containerId}` | After stop |
| List containers | `docker ps --filter label=gblockparty.pr={N}` | For finding preview containers |

